I will do a little read
up for our audiences

00:00:48.990 --> 00:00:50.060
out there, though.

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:54.420
So in 1971, Di Meola enrolled
in Berklee College of Music

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:59.720
in Boston, and in 1974,
started his musical journey.

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:01.870
In addition to his
prolific solo career,

00:01:01.870 --> 00:01:06.060
he's shared the stage with
Chick Corea, Stanley Clark,

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:10.240
Jan Hammer, Carlos Santana, Joan
McLaughlin, the late Paco de

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:14.050
Lucia, and Luciano Pavarotti
to mention just a few names

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:17.020
from a long list
of collaborators.

00:01:17.020 --> 00:01:20.250
Al coinvented invented fusion,
being one of the earliest

00:01:20.250 --> 00:01:22.680
pioneers of the genre.

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:24.290
And here's an interesting bit.

00:01:24.290 --> 00:01:29.170
He also co-created the concept
of the touring trio of equals

00:01:29.170 --> 00:01:32.760
after replacing Larry Coryell
in the acoustic guitar

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:35.840
group The Guitar Trio
and bring the concept

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:38.800
to widespread attention.

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:42.710
Al is a frequent at the
top of the US jazz charts.

00:01:42.710 --> 00:01:45.590
He has amassed over
20 albums as a leader

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:48.710
while collaborating
on a dozen of others,

00:01:48.710 --> 00:01:51.470
including with the
godfather of fusion,

00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:55.010
the earlier-mentioned Larry
Coryell, and Barry Miles,

00:01:55.010 --> 00:01:57.720
who's tape recording
launched Al's career

00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:01.790
in subsequent
collaboration with Corea.

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:08.380
He has been selected 11 times
as winner in best jazz guitarist

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:12.350
by the Guitar Player
Magazine reader poll.

00:02:12.350 --> 00:02:14.640
Guitar Player Magazine
is actually in San Bruno,

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:17.700
where YouTube is, as well.

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:22.030
If jazz is the original and most
influential American art forum,

00:02:22.030 --> 00:02:24.420
then Al Di Meola
is certainly one

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:29.450
of its most visible contemporary
composers and performers.

00:02:29.450 --> 00:02:32.500
He has become respected as
one of the most influential

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:35.220
guitarists in jazz to date.

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:39.640
A native of New Jersey who still
resides in the Garden State, Al

00:02:39.640 --> 00:02:44.710
Di Meola was born in Jersey
City on July 22, 1954,

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:49.010
growing up in Bergenfield with
the music of Elvis Presley,

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:51.570
The Ventures, and the Beatles.

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:53.933
Please join me in welcoming
Al Di Meola to Google.

00:02:53.933 --> 00:02:55.308
AL DI MEOLA: Thank
you very much.

00:02:55.308 --> 00:02:57.798
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:01.735 --> 00:03:03.110
AL DI MEOLA: It
was a great start

00:03:03.110 --> 00:03:08.640
to the day to google
Google just to get here.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:11.217
But I'm very happy to
be participating today.

00:03:11.217 --> 00:03:12.300
Thanks for the invitation.

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:14.246
BORIS DEBIC: We are
honored to have you here.

00:03:14.246 --> 00:03:15.370
AL DI MEOLA: This is great.

00:03:15.370 --> 00:03:17.680
BORIS DEBIC: You are a
legend a lot of these people

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:22.460
have listened to half
their lives if not longer.

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:23.820
So where shall we start?

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:25.890
With the beginnings, I guess.

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:28.567
I found this little tidbit.

00:03:28.567 --> 00:03:29.525
AL DI MEOLA: Which one?

00:03:29.525 --> 00:03:35.370
BORIS DEBIC: That your sister
was influential in developing

00:03:35.370 --> 00:03:36.214
you as a musician.

00:03:36.214 --> 00:03:38.630
AL DI MEOLA: Well, only because
she was seven years older.

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:41.380
So she was the one--
as I was a child,

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:44.700
she was the one that
came home with the 45s,

00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:46.350
with the hit records.

00:03:46.350 --> 00:03:50.350
And I got to hear the music.

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:54.960
And a lot of it was
quite inspiring.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:57.430
I guess the late
'50s, early '60s

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:02.520
were groundbreaking
in terms of sound.

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:05.670
The change over into
the '60s was something

00:04:05.670 --> 00:04:12.210
that we haven't seen since-- the
most inspiring creative period

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:15.630
of change was during
that whole decade.

00:04:15.630 --> 00:04:18.800
So she was largely
responsible for turning me

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:22.120
on to a lot of those
hits at the time.

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:26.960
Even the Beach Boys
were quite a sensation.

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:30.680
But it was the Beatles
that really did it for me.

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:33.010
And instrumental groups
like The Ventures

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:35.790
and all for the real guitar
heads, the surf bands,

00:04:35.790 --> 00:04:37.610
and stuff like that.

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:40.280
And then from there, then
you had all the English music

00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:44.430
that came over that
was groundbreaking and

00:04:44.430 --> 00:04:45.397
revolutionary, really.

00:04:45.397 --> 00:04:46.230
BORIS DEBIC: Indeed.

00:04:46.230 --> 00:04:47.410
Indeed it was.

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:49.560
AL DI MEOLA:
Compared to the '50s.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:51.130
BORIS DEBIC: So
tell me something.

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:53.434
How was it growing
up in New Jersey?

00:04:53.434 --> 00:04:54.350
That's very close to--

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:55.452
AL DI MEOLA: It was great.

00:04:55.452 --> 00:04:57.660
BORIS DEBIC: There's a lot
of things happening there.

00:04:57.660 --> 00:04:59.076
AL DI MEOLA: It
is a perfect place

00:04:59.076 --> 00:05:01.410
to grow up, because it
was quite middle class,

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:04.930
but it was close proximity
to New York City.

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:09.240
So we had all the record stores
that we needed all around us,

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:12.540
but we also had bus
transportation to take us

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:15.040
right into New York to
see the greatest shows

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:16.420
any night of the week.

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:19.440
So if I wasn't
down in the Village

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:22.440
seeing something at
the Fillmore East,

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:24.530
Bill Graham's
Fillmore East where

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:26.700
I got to see all
of those bands, all

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:28.750
of the legendary
bands from America,

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:33.660
from England on a weekly basis.

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:39.020
Just walking past Hendrix's
studio, Electric Lady Studio,

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:44.290
and the smell in the air,
the hippies everywhere.

00:05:44.290 --> 00:05:49.660
It was a quite inspiring time.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:51.270
And I just soaked it all in.

00:05:51.270 --> 00:05:55.010
And then in that same period,
I was visiting Latin clubs

00:05:55.010 --> 00:05:57.660
by myself, absorbing
the Latin music,

00:05:57.660 --> 00:06:00.930
and then later, the jazz
clubs that were everywhere

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:02.080
to be found.

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:05.620
So I was so fortunate
to grow up in Jersey

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:09.097
to have that proximity as
opposed to the Midwest.

00:06:09.097 --> 00:06:10.930
BORIS DEBIC: Did you
pick up the clubs first

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:12.480
or the guitar first?

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:14.910
AL DI MEOLA: No, the guitar.

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:18.230
Guitar was around
eight, nine years old.

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:20.380
I wasn't going to any
clubs at that time.

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:23.270
So did you play with Barry
before you went to college?

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:26.830
AL DI MEOLA: Well, Barry
Miles was the first time

00:06:26.830 --> 00:06:28.710
I went to Berklee
School of Music,

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:31.730
and we discovered
Barry's records.

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:35.200
He's really the first fusion
guy ever, before anyone.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:36.774
He kind of invented fusion.

00:06:36.774 --> 00:06:37.690
BORIS DEBIC: OK, stop.

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:39.140
I've got to stop you right here.

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:42.790
So for people who
are 16 now and who

00:06:42.790 --> 00:06:45.890
are like, what is this
guy talking about, fusion?

00:06:45.890 --> 00:06:48.770
Could you illustrate to us what
is fusion, and what is the--

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:51.620
AL DI MEOLA: Fusion was
really the culmination

00:06:51.620 --> 00:06:55.842
of rock blending with
elements of jazz, primarily.

00:06:55.842 --> 00:06:58.050
BORIS DEBIC: Is there a way
to show that on a guitar,

00:06:58.050 --> 00:06:59.400
by any chance?

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:00.140
AL DI MEOLA: No.

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:00.640
But anyway--

00:07:06.254 --> 00:07:08.170
BORIS DEBIC: I'll get
him to take that guitar.

00:07:08.170 --> 00:07:08.930
Trust me.

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:10.263
AL DI MEOLA: Of course there is.

00:07:10.263 --> 00:07:15.890
Well, we have other elements
that we infuse-- Latin rhythms,

00:07:15.890 --> 00:07:19.020
classical elements as well.

00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:21.715
So I would take something
from a classical realm,

00:07:21.715 --> 00:07:27.810
and I would syncopate the
rhythm to give it a swing.

00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:30.830
Or it could be
something that-- it

00:07:30.830 --> 00:07:34.400
could be a Beatles song, which
you would relate to pop music.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:38.600
But some of that music had
such beautiful harmony.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:39.990
Of course, it had
a great melody.

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:41.630
But it had beautiful
harmony, which

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:44.410
gives you the basis
for improvisation

00:07:44.410 --> 00:07:45.820
if you want to do that.

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:47.890
Because the Beatles
really never did that.

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:50.010
The focus was on the
lyric and the voice

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:54.700
and the beautiful
song in itself.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:58.070
I had the good
fortune of coming up

00:07:58.070 --> 00:08:01.290
with the idea of
recording a record

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:03.070
of a collection of their work.

00:08:03.070 --> 00:08:07.062
But then doing it at
Abbey Road made it

00:08:07.062 --> 00:08:09.990
like going to Disney
World as a kid.

00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:12.419
BORIS DEBIC: And we'll come
to that later on in the talk.

00:08:12.419 --> 00:08:13.960
AL DI MEOLA: So you
can take harmony.

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:16.550
You can take simple harmony
and improvise on it,

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:18.520
maybe change the
harmony a little bit.

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:21.100
And then you have elements
of jazz in that sense,

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:24.530
because you're improvising
with scales as opposed to rock

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:27.750
pentatonic licks.

00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:30.390
Rock pentatonic licks really
involve your first finger

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:32.240
and your third finger.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:33.820
You'll never see
a rock guitarist

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:35.669
use his second finger,
except for when

00:08:35.669 --> 00:08:38.450
he's mad at somebody,
and his pinkie.

00:08:41.058 --> 00:08:43.179
How do you like that?

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:43.929
Watch Clapton.

00:08:43.929 --> 00:08:46.110
He only uses his first
and third finger.

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:47.260
Because they're not--

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:49.440
BORIS DEBIC: And he's
called the god of guitar.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:51.060
AL DI MEOLA: Well,
back then, he was.

00:08:51.060 --> 00:08:52.310
BORIS DEBIC: Back then he was.

00:08:54.692 --> 00:08:55.900
So I was thinking about this.

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:59.120
The trio that you later
did with Paco de Lucia

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:03.760
and John McLaughlin were
three equals on guitars,

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:07.680
come and play-- that invented,
actually, a whole new genre

00:09:07.680 --> 00:09:10.320
of-- you had trios before.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:13.750
I read somewhere that
in classical music,

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:17.190
there were trios in the 1800s.

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:20.830
But those were like a cello
and piano and something else.

00:09:20.830 --> 00:09:22.800
It's not the same instrument.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:25.440
So these guys sit together
and they play guitars

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:27.030
all between themselves.

00:09:27.030 --> 00:09:31.990
I said to myself if Clapton
is the god of guitar--

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:33.590
and sorry for the blasphemy.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:35.810
He meant it as inspiration.

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:38.820
Then these guys are
the holy trinity.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:40.970
AL DI MEOLA: Well, it
was a certain technique

00:09:40.970 --> 00:09:45.310
that we had-- Paco coming from
a flamenco tradition, which

00:09:45.310 --> 00:09:47.560
John and I did not come from.

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:50.140
But I was kind of like the guy
in the middle, the guy that

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:54.410
came from a Latin background--
not necessarily flamenco--

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:57.010
and John coming from a whole
different kind of thing,

00:09:57.010 --> 00:10:01.340
more Indian influenced
and very British in a way.

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:03.520
And so it just
worked, because we

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:05.800
had a certain
degree of technique

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:09.760
that we could communicate and
converse back and forth with.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:11.910
And we were probably three
of the only guys that

00:10:11.910 --> 00:10:13.810
could do that at that time.

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:16.700
So we made this record in 1980.

00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:21.710
After two months of touring
every single night starting

00:10:21.710 --> 00:10:24.400
in Europe, we just
built up our chops.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.810
And we were on fire by the
time we got San Francisco,

00:10:27.810 --> 00:10:30.280
and recorded a
record that became

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:33.510
this multi-zillion selling
record of a live record, which

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:36.500
at the time cost about
$2,000 or $3,000 to make

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:38.920
and sold something like
5 to 10 million copies,

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:40.160
somewhere in between.

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:42.880
We'll never know for sure
where the royalty went.

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:46.585
But it was a huge record
called "Friday Night

00:10:46.585 --> 00:10:48.280
in San Francisco."

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:48.890
Yeah.

00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:49.840
Some of you know it.

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:51.520
BORIS DEBIC: You got that.

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:52.810
Show it to the camera.

00:10:52.810 --> 00:10:54.350
AL DI MEOLA: You know, there's
a number on the back of it.

00:10:54.350 --> 00:10:55.740
It will tell me if I got paid.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:57.131
Let me see.

00:10:57.131 --> 00:10:58.380
There's a serial number on it.

00:10:58.380 --> 00:10:58.590
No.

00:10:58.590 --> 00:10:59.340
You owe me a buck.

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:05.880
Look at that, how
ridiculous I look in there.

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:07.620
That's great.

00:11:07.620 --> 00:11:09.840
There's actually a "Saturday
Night in San Francisco,"

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:15.480
too that I have in my studio
that will be released someday

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.794
on a little chip, probably.

00:11:17.794 --> 00:11:18.460
BORIS DEBIC: OK.

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:21.990
We jumped a little bit,
so I wanted to go back.

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:23.110
We mentioned the trio.

00:11:23.110 --> 00:11:25.680
The trio actually
has its origins

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:29.910
with Larry Correal,
who was christened

00:11:29.910 --> 00:11:31.530
the godfather of fusion.

00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:33.292
So can you talk a
little bit about--

00:11:33.292 --> 00:11:35.750
AL DI MEOLA: Larry was a big
hero of mine when I was a kid.

00:11:35.750 --> 00:11:38.350
So he was really the
first guitar player

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:41.050
that blended all the elements.

00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:44.340
He's really a jazz guy that
brought in rock elements

00:11:44.340 --> 00:11:46.280
and country music elements.

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:48.670
Right after the heyday
of that whole rock

00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:52.940
scene and the Fillmore East, I
was looking for something more.

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:56.140
And he was the guy that I became
familiar with and friendly

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:56.970
with.

00:11:56.970 --> 00:12:00.040
And I actually took a lesson
from him, too, at one point.

00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:03.012
BORIS DEBIC: Can you share the
lesson with the young viewers?

00:12:03.012 --> 00:12:04.970
AL DI MEOLA: You want me
to remember the lesson

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:06.310
from when I was 15?

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:07.831
BORIS DEBIC: Was
it a guitar lesson?

00:12:07.831 --> 00:12:09.580
AL DI MEOLA: Yeah, it
was a guitar lesson.

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:10.246
BORIS DEBIC: Oh.

00:12:10.246 --> 00:12:12.670
I thought it was one of
those philosophical lessons.

00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:13.420
AL DI MEOLA: Yeah.

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:15.705
He was tripping the whole
time, so I'm not sure

00:12:15.705 --> 00:12:18.074
if it was usable
whatever he showed me.

00:12:18.074 --> 00:12:18.740
BORIS DEBIC: OK.

00:12:18.740 --> 00:12:21.320
Maybe not the right lesson
for our younger audience.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:22.903
AL DI MEOLA: But
he's a wonderful guy.

00:12:22.903 --> 00:12:24.500
He's still around.

00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:29.900
He's kind of like the Keith
Richards of fusion music.

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:32.199
I don't know how he
lived through it all.

00:12:32.199 --> 00:12:33.740
BORIS DEBIC: That's
very nice of you.

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:36.520
We have a couple of people who
have a burning question there.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:38.139
So sir.

